00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:57.440
So R and BigQuery for data science.

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:02.160
So here is a chart that my teammate Priyanka

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:04.960
put out recently about all the different tools

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:07.160
on Google Cloud for data science.

00:03:08.360 --> 00:03:10.919
And you can see that there's a lot, right, quite frankly.

00:03:10.919 --> 00:03:14.119
So depending on how wide your definition of data science is,

00:03:14.119 --> 00:03:15.960
and here we picked a pretty wide one,

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:18.240
there are lots of different categories of activities

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:20.880
that fall into data science.

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:24.839
So you can see here we have things like data engineering,

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:28.240
right, so all the aspects of getting data in,

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:31.399
ingestion, pre-processing storage, et cetera.

00:03:31.399 --> 00:03:33.039
Data analysis, which is fairly common,

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:35.240
something that a lot of people using R will do too,

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:37.800
is exploratory data, whether you're getting stuff,

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:40.720
maybe you go right from there into an activation

00:03:41.119 --> 00:03:44.800
in a dashboard tool, or you want to go build a model.

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:46.440
And depending on how you want to build a model

00:03:46.440 --> 00:03:49.679
and how large and sophisticated

00:03:49.679 --> 00:03:53.080
and sort of what the goal of that model is,

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:55.960
there's a ton of tools here you may want to use.

00:03:55.960 --> 00:03:58.320
And then once you sort of have your model

00:03:58.320 --> 00:03:59.160
and it's up and running,

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:01.199
now you're sort of in the software engineering space

00:04:01.199 --> 00:04:05.320
for you want to manage your model and all the end points.

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:08.160
This is where, certainly from my background statistics,

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:09.080
that this is new to me.

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:11.160
You end up having to learn a bunch of technology

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:13.919
just about what to do once you've kind of done

00:04:13.919 --> 00:04:16.000
what I would consider the statistical work.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.720
And then finally, kind of the most important end goal

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:20.760
is these activation points.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:22.040
You're not doing data analysis,

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:23.920
data science in a vacuum usually,

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:26.200
you're trying to influence some sort of business decision,

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:28.279
or it'll go into an application, right?

00:04:28.279 --> 00:04:31.399
Your model will be part of software

00:04:31.399 --> 00:04:34.119
that sort of dictates how your business,

00:04:34.119 --> 00:04:36.920
that will be an integrated one to your business,

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:37.920
I should say.

00:04:37.959 --> 00:04:40.959
So I could spend the next several hours

00:04:40.959 --> 00:04:42.880
deep diving into these products.

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:44.600
I'm not going to do that.

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:46.839
I'm only going to talk about probably one of them

00:04:46.839 --> 00:04:49.079
and then maybe mention some others as we go.

00:04:49.079 --> 00:04:53.320
So the big idea is we can turn data into insights, right?

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:57.119
Faster and easier with tools like these various ones.

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:02.519
The one product I do want to talk about is BigQuery.

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:07.320
So Google Cloud BigQuery is a serverless,

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:10.399
highly scalable and cost-effective data warehouse.

00:05:10.399 --> 00:05:12.279
We have many customers using this

00:05:12.279 --> 00:05:16.040
that you store up to 100 plus petabytes of data, right?

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:18.519
So that's well larger than any of the data

00:05:18.519 --> 00:05:19.799
we're going to talk about today,

00:05:19.799 --> 00:05:22.440
but is starting to become pretty common

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:23.720
in the enterprise space, right?

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:26.119
Where companies have more and more data.

00:05:26.119 --> 00:05:31.119
So it's SQL-based, highly available data warehouse.

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:32.959
Some of the unique things it has

00:05:32.959 --> 00:05:35.040
is the ability to go multi-cloud.

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:37.160
So you can query stuff that's on Google Cloud

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:38.839
within BigQuery itself,

00:05:38.839 --> 00:05:43.279
but also in other clouds with a product called BigQuery Omni.

00:05:43.279 --> 00:05:45.079
There's also real-time insights.

00:05:45.079 --> 00:05:47.600
So based on streaming data into Google Cloud

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:48.440
with other tools,

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:52.239
you can set up dashboards or other sort of interfaces

00:05:52.239 --> 00:05:53.799
where the data coming into your warehouse

00:05:53.799 --> 00:05:56.720
is available to you very, very quickly.

00:05:56.720 --> 00:05:58.480
There's also built-in machine learning.

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:02.040
So through a product called BigQuery ML,

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:03.279
BigQuery Machine Learning,

00:06:03.279 --> 00:06:05.200
you can fit a growing number of models,

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:07.600
including linear regression, logistic regression,

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:09.359
onto neural networks.

00:06:10.519 --> 00:06:12.279
Things that Cisco R users

00:06:12.279 --> 00:06:14.279
might be interested in too, pre-processing.

00:06:14.279 --> 00:06:15.440
And that's a really nice tool

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:18.160
for when you have really huge data already in BigQuery,

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:20.000
you can do the machine learning right on that data.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:21.559
You don't have to move it around.

00:06:21.559 --> 00:06:24.200
And then insights for everyone.

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:26.519
Products like BI Engine allow you

00:06:26.519 --> 00:06:30.279
to kind of scale the way you take BigQuery

00:06:30.279 --> 00:06:31.920
and build outputs on top of it.

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:35.239
So this is one of my favorite products.

00:06:35.239 --> 00:06:37.679
This was kind of came out of work that Google was doing.

00:06:37.679 --> 00:06:39.399
Obviously, Google is a huge data company.

00:06:39.399 --> 00:06:41.000
The whole concept of Google Cloud

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.200
is taking the infrastructure that powers things

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:45.000
like Google Search, like YouTube,

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:47.839
and making that available for other businesses.

00:06:50.959 --> 00:06:53.600
Okay, so now let's get a little bit into this

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:57.600
as far as R and BigQuery.

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:00.720
So I like R and I like BigQuery.

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:04.160
So this isn't, which one is better for what?

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:06.040
You can do a lot of things in both of them.

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:08.399
And a lot of that will be based on sort of the use case.

00:07:08.399 --> 00:07:09.399
When I go through the example,

00:07:09.399 --> 00:07:11.959
you'll see how I'm kind of weaving between the two.

00:07:11.959 --> 00:07:13.959
But in general, things I like to do in R

00:07:13.959 --> 00:07:16.480
include getting data from lots of different packages.

00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:18.320
We'll see on here, websites, APIs.

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:21.480
I think the ecosystem around how to get data into R

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:23.640
has been really awesome

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:26.279
and getting better over the last several years.

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:27.519
General data manipulation.

00:07:27.519 --> 00:07:30.600
Obviously, the tidyverse is quite amazing for this.

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:33.239
I use it all the time extensively.

00:07:34.399 --> 00:07:36.760
And yeah, can't recommend that part enough.

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:39.799
Exploratory data analysis.

00:07:39.799 --> 00:07:43.920
You know, whether that's just kind of looking at your data

00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:46.640
or plotting it with ggplot2, something like that.

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:48.000
Statistical analysis and modeling.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:51.040
This is where I think R has a large depth of packages,

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:52.920
right, depending on where your background is,

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:54.720
what type of specific model you want.

00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:56.559
You can almost always find an R package

00:07:56.559 --> 00:07:58.079
or multiple that are doing,

00:07:58.079 --> 00:07:59.480
that are available to solve your problem.

00:07:59.480 --> 00:08:02.040
And then what I call ad hoc data visualization.

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:04.559
As I'm going, I want to look at something,

00:08:04.559 --> 00:08:07.119
quickly build a plot, quickly, maybe facet the plot

00:08:07.119 --> 00:08:08.600
by a couple of different dimensions

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:12.119
or look at a few things as I'm doing analysis.

00:08:12.119 --> 00:08:14.079
R, I think, really stands out for that.

00:08:14.079 --> 00:08:16.640
BigQuery, like we said, enterprise data warehouse.

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:19.799
So if you want a bunch of data that is now available for R,

00:08:19.799 --> 00:08:21.119
but maybe lots of other things,

00:08:21.119 --> 00:08:26.119
that's like the place where we want that data to be stored.

00:08:27.119 --> 00:08:29.920
And then, and we'll look into this a little bit too,

00:08:29.920 --> 00:08:31.839
what I call intermediate pieces,

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:33.840
some views, stored procedures.

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:35.200
Often you'll have a data warehouse

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:40.200
with like some very, I guess, basic foundational tables.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:42.039
But then on top of that,

00:08:42.039 --> 00:08:45.280
you want to create some more interesting outputs

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:48.039
that then maybe feed multiple other analyses, right?

00:08:48.039 --> 00:08:50.239
So we'll talk a little bit about this too.

00:08:50.239 --> 00:08:52.799
And then we talked a little bit about BigQuery ML.

00:08:52.799 --> 00:08:55.400
So BigQuery also can do modeling,

00:08:55.479 --> 00:08:59.080
which is a differentiating feature for a data warehouse.

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:00.840
And like I said, I like using that

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:03.799
when you have really big data already in BigQuery.

00:09:03.799 --> 00:09:08.799
And the storing, we also, like I talked about,

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:12.080
you can store the results in BigQuery of an analysis, right?

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:13.960
Not just the base sort of data, the results,

00:09:13.960 --> 00:09:15.760
and then build sort of interactive dashboards

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:19.440
or other data products off of them as well.

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:20.599
And then the thing at the bottom,

00:09:20.599 --> 00:09:22.559
maybe one thing that like, if you want to take away,

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:24.119
maybe you've already, if you're not using this,

00:09:24.119 --> 00:09:25.640
but if you are using R

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:27.280
and maybe you're interested in BigQuery,

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:30.679
the big R query package is really a strong way

00:09:30.679 --> 00:09:32.960
to integrate the two.

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:35.559
So you want to get data from BigQuery into R,

00:09:35.559 --> 00:09:37.320
you want to take data from R into BigQuery.

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:40.159
I use this package all the time to do this sort of stuff.

00:09:40.159 --> 00:09:44.039
Thanks to Jenny Bryan and Hadley at the RStudio team.

00:09:44.039 --> 00:09:45.520
I believe they're the developers

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:47.159
and maintainers of that package.

00:09:49.359 --> 00:09:53.000
Okay, so let's dive into an example analysis here

00:09:53.919 --> 00:09:56.840
where we're going to use NCAA basketball data,

00:09:56.840 --> 00:10:00.520
March Madness, not too far around the corner.

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:03.599
And I have an interest in college basketball data

00:10:03.599 --> 00:10:06.000
going back to, I don't know, probably when I was a kid,

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:09.559
but also from ESPN where I worked on the original version

00:10:09.559 --> 00:10:11.440
of our basketball power index,

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:14.679
which launched about almost 10 years ago to the day.

00:10:14.679 --> 00:10:15.919
So I thought it would be a cool way

00:10:15.919 --> 00:10:20.200
to get into the idea of using R and BigQuery together

00:10:20.200 --> 00:10:23.640
and see what we can learn about NCAA basketball.

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:25.520
So first I'll set the problem

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:28.679
and then assuming I know how to switch my screen,

00:10:28.679 --> 00:10:32.080
I'll share other aspects of,

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:34.039
share some R code as well as BigQuery.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:37.559
So here's what we want to do today,

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:40.239
which is to create a rating system

00:10:40.239 --> 00:10:43.119
for NCAA basketball players.

00:10:43.119 --> 00:10:45.760
So this is not novel.

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:47.840
Some people have done this type of thing,

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:49.520
creating rating systems,

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:51.960
a player rating system is among one of the top

00:10:51.960 --> 00:10:54.280
sort of topics in sports analytics.

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:58.119
But the difference here is that we want

00:10:58.119 --> 00:11:02.320
a couple of different things to be true about this system.

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:05.719
So we want to use multiple player box score statistics.

00:11:05.719 --> 00:11:07.559
So for example, we don't want to just take the player

00:11:07.559 --> 00:11:10.000
who scored the most points and say that's the best

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:11.159
and something like that, right?

00:11:11.159 --> 00:11:14.359
There's many ways that people can contribute to the game.

00:11:14.359 --> 00:11:15.440
In the world of NBA,

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:18.479
there's actually way more interesting statistics now

00:11:18.479 --> 00:11:22.039
that take into account sort of play-by-play level,

00:11:22.039 --> 00:11:23.080
who's on the court,

00:11:24.239 --> 00:11:27.320
all the way to the newer tracking data to do this.

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:29.799
But we're going to assume we have more limited data,

00:11:29.799 --> 00:11:33.400
but still very good on the player box score level.

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:35.280
We want to take all of that into account

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:36.719
or as much as we can.

00:11:36.719 --> 00:11:39.320
And then the second point is important as well.

00:11:39.320 --> 00:11:40.280
We want to represent it

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:41.760
as a player's contribution to winning.

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:43.400
So let's say we had really detailed data,

00:11:43.400 --> 00:11:45.239
we could say who jumps the highest.

00:11:45.919 --> 00:11:46.760
That would be a way to rate players,

00:11:46.760 --> 00:11:48.880
but it doesn't necessarily in and of itself

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:50.039
contribute to winning.

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:53.039
So we want to take into account statistics,

00:11:53.039 --> 00:11:55.479
but also have some relationship with winning.

00:11:56.520 --> 00:11:59.760
The third point is important as well.

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:02.000
So often I've seen a lot of rating system

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.159
for men's college basketball,

00:12:03.159 --> 00:12:05.400
not quite as many for women's college basketball,

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.080
but I think it's growing over time.

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:07.960
We want a rating system

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:10.440
that can be equally applicable to both.

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:14.359
Many statistics are collected on sort of both levels.

00:12:14.359 --> 00:12:16.479
Let's see, again, we want to talk about scaling.

00:12:16.479 --> 00:12:20.640
Can we take the same system and adapt it for,

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:22.000
I shouldn't say adapt it from one to the other.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:23.039
Can we take the same system

00:12:23.039 --> 00:12:26.039
and create it for men's and women's basketball?

00:12:26.039 --> 00:12:28.080
And then we want to apply it to the current system,

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:29.799
but again, this is about scale.

00:12:29.799 --> 00:12:33.039
We want to compare to players in past years as well.

00:12:33.039 --> 00:12:35.440
So let's apply it to the few past years.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:38.559
And then this last point, which is really important,

00:12:38.559 --> 00:12:39.919
we want to adjust for schedule.

00:12:39.919 --> 00:12:44.039
We don't want to just take into account stats as they are.

00:12:44.719 --> 00:12:46.520
We know that in Division I college basketball,

00:12:46.520 --> 00:12:49.359
there are over 350 teams each, men's and women's,

00:12:49.359 --> 00:12:51.119
and teams play varying schedules,

00:12:51.119 --> 00:12:53.080
all different sorts of quality.

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:56.960
We want to adjust for who, not just, you know,

00:12:56.960 --> 00:12:58.359
we want to account for not just what you did,

00:12:58.359 --> 00:12:59.559
but who you did it against.

00:12:59.559 --> 00:13:01.159
And that's really important, so.

00:13:04.239 --> 00:13:07.280
So why is this, why would this be important or useful?

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:09.679
So there's like some basis,

00:13:09.679 --> 00:13:11.159
like people say that all-in-one ratings

00:13:11.159 --> 00:13:13.000
are dangerous and shouldn't be.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:15.520
Sort of consumed.

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:18.280
And there definitely are reasons why you don't want them,

00:13:18.280 --> 00:13:20.520
particularly in certain instances

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:23.479
where you want to learn more about a player,

00:13:23.479 --> 00:13:25.840
especially if you're coaching the players on your team.

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:28.640
You want to talk more about what that player's strengths are,

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:30.880
how they fit in with the rest of the team.

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:32.599
It's not just an overall value thing.

00:13:32.599 --> 00:13:34.400
But let me take the other side

00:13:34.400 --> 00:13:37.320
and talk about why they really are useful sometimes.

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:39.000
So for media and fans, right?

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.239
A lot of people in college basketball otherwise

00:13:41.239 --> 00:13:42.840
always talking about who's the best player,

00:13:43.679 --> 00:13:44.520
who should make a certain team,

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:46.039
who should be an All-American,

00:13:46.039 --> 00:13:47.840
who should win the awards.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:49.000
And these all-in-one ratings

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:50.640
are really useful for that, right?

00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:52.520
Because one player may be really good on defense,

00:13:52.520 --> 00:13:54.159
one's good on offense, one scores more,

00:13:54.159 --> 00:13:55.119
one rebounds more.

00:13:55.119 --> 00:13:56.479
How do we know, right?

00:13:56.479 --> 00:13:59.599
And these metrics give us a really good baseline

00:13:59.599 --> 00:14:02.520
for some of those discussions, as well as research, right?

00:14:02.520 --> 00:14:04.960
So you may be watching a game or in your media,

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:06.520
you need to call a game.

00:14:06.520 --> 00:14:10.760
College basketball, again, 350 plus teams on either side.

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:12.440
So that's thousands of players each year.

00:14:13.039 --> 00:14:14.520
The players change out often, right?

00:14:14.520 --> 00:14:15.799
Because they're moving through,

00:14:15.799 --> 00:14:16.960
especially some of the best players

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:18.520
go right on to the pros.

00:14:18.520 --> 00:14:21.400
So just having an idea of who are the best players

00:14:21.400 --> 00:14:23.559
on certain teams can be really useful.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:26.359
So that's one use case.

00:14:26.359 --> 00:14:28.599
And again, in my time at ESPN,

00:14:28.599 --> 00:14:30.760
this is a lot of reason why we would develop

00:14:30.760 --> 00:14:32.559
these player ratings.

00:14:32.559 --> 00:14:34.479
College teams, right, would find this useful

00:14:34.479 --> 00:14:35.640
for managing their own roster,

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:37.359
as well as looking at their opponents,

00:14:37.359 --> 00:14:39.880
who are the best players on those teams.

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:40.719
Content companies.

00:14:40.719 --> 00:14:42.000
So I'm thinking more here,

00:14:42.559 --> 00:14:47.080
like even sort of the companies getting into daily fantasy

00:14:47.080 --> 00:14:49.119
or more coverage of gambling and sports.

00:14:50.239 --> 00:14:51.880
To something, even a company like Google,

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:53.840
like if you have an all-in-one rating,

00:14:53.840 --> 00:14:54.919
what could you do with that?

00:14:54.919 --> 00:14:57.000
You might use it to figure out signals

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:58.359
for which players might be interesting,

00:14:58.359 --> 00:15:01.080
what players are people looking for content for,

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:03.080
above and beyond how good they kind of are at winning.

00:15:03.080 --> 00:15:05.080
It's just a measure of how interesting they are.

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:07.919
It could be a signal in a machine learning model, right?

00:15:07.919 --> 00:15:10.200
And then finally, we're talking about college ratings.

00:15:10.200 --> 00:15:12.359
Pro teams may find these ratings interesting

00:15:12.359 --> 00:15:15.000
because they want to evaluate, again, it could be NBA,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.640
it could be WNBA, evaluating the college players

00:15:17.640 --> 00:15:20.080
as potential draft prospects.

00:15:20.080 --> 00:15:22.119
And along with many other things, right,

00:15:22.119 --> 00:15:26.440
measurables and sort of how they do in interviews and things,

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:29.200
you might want to use these all-in-one sort of ratings.

00:15:31.280 --> 00:15:35.400
Okay, so this is the one sort of high-level overview

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:36.359
about what we're going to do.

00:15:36.359 --> 00:15:38.640
I'm gonna try to at least walk through this.

00:15:38.640 --> 00:15:39.840
I won't say fully demo this.

00:15:40.479 --> 00:15:41.719
I'm gonna try to walk through this as much as we can.

00:15:41.719 --> 00:15:46.000
But high-level, we're going to use open-source R packages,

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:50.039
which exist, thankfully, to pull in NCAA basketball data.

00:15:50.039 --> 00:15:51.479
And then we're gonna upload it to BigQuery,

00:15:51.479 --> 00:15:54.520
kind of create our mini data warehouse.

00:15:54.520 --> 00:15:57.799
And then instead of sort of reinventing the wheel,

00:15:57.799 --> 00:16:00.359
we're gonna use existing basketball analytics theory

00:16:00.359 --> 00:16:04.280
for how to kind of take player stats

00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:05.679
and create a measure of how much

00:16:05.679 --> 00:16:07.159
they impact their team's winning.

00:16:07.159 --> 00:16:09.119
And we're gonna apply that in BigQuery.

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:12.520
We're gonna read that data back into R

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:14.080
for our schedule adjustment.

00:16:14.080 --> 00:16:15.200
And then since it's there,

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:16.320
we're gonna calculate some stuff there

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:19.479
and get some final player ratings.

00:16:19.479 --> 00:16:22.080
And it'll push it back into BigQuery.

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:24.159
And then once we start looking at them there,

00:16:24.159 --> 00:16:26.280
we'll do the whole purpose of player ratings,

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:28.239
which is for argument, is for debate.

00:16:28.239 --> 00:16:29.960
So we'll say, well, this player's ranked too high,

00:16:29.960 --> 00:16:31.400
this player's ranked too low.

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:33.719
And to some degree, that at least,

00:16:33.719 --> 00:16:34.719
once I got comfortable with that,

00:16:34.719 --> 00:16:38.000
I took things, I found it more interesting.

00:16:38.679 --> 00:16:40.119
No one's gonna take your player rating system

00:16:40.119 --> 00:16:41.200
and say, oh, this is perfect.

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:43.760
And they shouldn't, and you shouldn't either.

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:47.080
So it's a good baseline for a lot of the reasons

00:16:47.080 --> 00:16:49.039
we discussed and then you go from there.

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:54.799
Okay, so let's go through a setup here.

00:16:56.880 --> 00:17:00.599
So normally I don't include code directly on the slide,

00:17:00.599 --> 00:17:03.760
at least like this, but I really wanna point out

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:06.079
how awesome sort of the ecosystem is here.

00:17:06.079 --> 00:17:09.439
So major thanks is at the bottom to Saim Gilani.

00:17:10.280 --> 00:17:13.439
So he sort of is the leader of this initiative

00:17:13.439 --> 00:17:14.920
around the sports dataverse,

00:17:14.920 --> 00:17:17.520
and has been a developer on many packages

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:22.520
to kind of make sports data accessible in R,

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:23.760
as well as Python and others,

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:25.160
but we're focusing on R today.

00:17:25.160 --> 00:17:27.400
So the two you see here, hoopr and wehoop,

00:17:28.359 --> 00:17:31.400
one of them allows you access to men's basketball data

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:34.479
and the other, as you might imagine, women's basketball data.

00:17:34.479 --> 00:17:37.560
And this is the full code to get a bunch of data

00:17:37.560 --> 00:17:42.439
for the history of what's available in this package

00:17:42.439 --> 00:17:43.880
for men's and women's college basketball.

00:17:43.880 --> 00:17:46.119
So it's about almost 20 years,

00:17:46.119 --> 00:17:49.520
but not as complete here and 15 for women.

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:53.199
And you can get teams, schedule, team box, player box,

00:17:53.199 --> 00:17:57.239
just by running these very well-named functions,

00:17:57.239 --> 00:17:59.479
load the schedule, load the box.

00:17:59.479 --> 00:18:01.839
And the other good thing, so again,

00:18:01.839 --> 00:18:05.920
this in times where we were working in environment,

00:18:05.920 --> 00:18:07.439
this will not be as easy, right?

00:18:07.439 --> 00:18:10.079
Go getting your data is a day's week's process.

00:18:10.079 --> 00:18:11.319
This was not the case in this.

00:18:11.319 --> 00:18:13.239
So again, major thanks to Saim

00:18:13.239 --> 00:18:14.359
for setting up these packages,

00:18:14.359 --> 00:18:16.239
others who have contributed as well.

00:18:16.239 --> 00:18:17.239
You can get all the data here.

00:18:17.239 --> 00:18:18.640
And the other good thing about this

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:19.959
is that the men's and women's data

00:18:19.959 --> 00:18:21.599
comes in with the same schema.

00:18:21.599 --> 00:18:23.280
So now when we talk about scaling,

00:18:24.319 --> 00:18:27.800
one thing we can do is actually store them together,

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:29.760
add an extra field that says this is men's basketball,

00:18:29.760 --> 00:18:30.839
this is women's.

00:18:30.839 --> 00:18:32.239
And then every calculation we do,

00:18:32.239 --> 00:18:34.680
we can group by that sport category

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:37.160
and everything else kind of can flow along.

00:18:37.160 --> 00:18:40.839
And we don't have to create two separate code bases

00:18:40.839 --> 00:18:43.239
or whatever for rating these players.

00:18:45.920 --> 00:18:50.920
Okay, this might be the most complicated slide, not sure.

00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:54.680
So the other thing is, like I said,

00:18:54.680 --> 00:18:58.160
we want to build on foundations that others have built

00:18:58.160 --> 00:19:00.160
for how to measure basketball players.

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:04.520
So the framework I use here is actually fairly old,

00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:07.319
at least old as much relative to sports analytics goes.

00:19:07.319 --> 00:19:09.280
So this is based on using box score statistics.

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:10.280
Again, if you have play-by-play,

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:11.439
you have more detailed tracking data,

00:19:11.439 --> 00:19:12.959
you can do plenty of other things.

00:19:12.959 --> 00:19:15.680
But this, we have box score data going back,

00:19:15.680 --> 00:19:18.760
you know, about a decade or so for both men's and women's,

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:23.280
thanks to the Hoobar and WeHoop packages.

00:19:23.280 --> 00:19:25.560
So let's do our best to use that

00:19:25.599 --> 00:19:28.319
and add some of our own twists to it too.

00:19:28.319 --> 00:19:30.319
So you have player box score stats,

00:19:30.319 --> 00:19:32.640
you have team box score stats.

00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:35.239
There's a whole lot of math developed by Dean Oliver,

00:19:35.239 --> 00:19:37.920
who I was fortunate enough to work with at ESPN

00:19:37.920 --> 00:19:39.839
and is a pioneer in the basketball analytics space,

00:19:39.839 --> 00:19:41.880
currently works as a coach for the Wizards.

00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:43.560
He wrote this book, Basketball on Paper,

00:19:43.560 --> 00:19:45.479
and did a bunch of stuff to show

00:19:45.479 --> 00:19:47.160
how you can get the most usage out of that

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:49.640
to create these individual player offensive

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:52.760
and defensive ratings, or rating, debrating.

00:19:52.760 --> 00:19:54.599
If you're familiar with basketball analytics,

00:19:54.599 --> 00:19:56.439
there's a concept called offensive

00:19:56.439 --> 00:19:59.359
and defensive efficiency, points for 100 possessions.

00:19:59.359 --> 00:20:01.640
These are the individual analogs to those.

00:20:01.640 --> 00:20:03.479
It's not the same as what the team does

00:20:03.479 --> 00:20:04.560
when the player's on the court,

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:06.400
it's a much more detailed calculation,

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:08.119
certainly on the offensive side,

00:20:08.119 --> 00:20:10.640
using points assists relative to the team

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:12.400
and how well the team did overall,

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:14.719
but taking into account the player's

00:20:14.719 --> 00:20:16.520
sort of credit for each of those things.

00:20:16.520 --> 00:20:18.520
The offensive one is much more detailed

00:20:18.520 --> 00:20:20.239
and useful than the defensive one,

00:20:20.239 --> 00:20:23.599
because box score is traditionally very offensive based.

00:20:24.760 --> 00:20:26.560
But you can calculate those things,

00:20:26.560 --> 00:20:28.560
you can calculate how many possessions

00:20:28.560 --> 00:20:29.800
the offensive player used,

00:20:29.800 --> 00:20:31.199
as well as how many defensive possessions

00:20:31.199 --> 00:20:32.319
they were involved in.

00:20:33.599 --> 00:20:36.439
And then with that and some other stats on league,

00:20:36.439 --> 00:20:40.280
again, I'm hand-waving a bunch on these big green arrows,

00:20:40.280 --> 00:20:42.599
but Sports Reference, among others,

00:20:42.599 --> 00:20:44.319
has a win-shares calculation.

00:20:44.319 --> 00:20:46.079
So they've detailed it here.

00:20:46.079 --> 00:20:47.439
I hope to share these slides afterwards

00:20:47.439 --> 00:20:49.439
so y'all can click the links and everything.

00:20:49.439 --> 00:20:51.479
But you can take those metrics

00:20:51.479 --> 00:20:54.000
and then do a bunch more math

00:20:54.079 --> 00:20:56.959
and develop these calculations

00:20:56.959 --> 00:20:59.319
for offensive and defensive win-shares,

00:20:59.319 --> 00:21:02.040
which then you can do another calculation,

00:21:02.040 --> 00:21:05.199
just add addition, so I didn't put a green arrow here,

00:21:05.199 --> 00:21:06.719
to get total win-shares.

00:21:06.719 --> 00:21:08.640
And then I have this other adjustment here

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:10.800
that I have seen and like,

00:21:10.800 --> 00:21:13.359
which is for college basketball in particular,

00:21:13.359 --> 00:21:15.319
win-shares is a low baseline.

00:21:15.319 --> 00:21:18.040
Everyone gets kind of wins relative to the team.

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:19.280
But what I'm more interested in,

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:20.800
how many wins does the player add

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:22.760
above sort of the average Division I player,

00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:24.719
whether that be men's or women's.

00:21:24.719 --> 00:21:27.199
So that's the final sort of piece here.

00:21:27.199 --> 00:21:29.280
So again, a lot of pieces I'm glossing over,

00:21:29.280 --> 00:21:32.280
not gonna go over this in detail,

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:33.439
but you can get the idea

00:21:33.439 --> 00:21:36.119
that we take player and team box score stats

00:21:36.119 --> 00:21:37.640
and end up with some metric

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:42.640
about how player contributes to his or her team's winnings.

