They may be very valuable to their teams,

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:19.280
but we didn't finish here, right?

00:32:19.280 --> 00:32:23.400
We didn't do our schedule adjustment, right?

00:32:23.400 --> 00:32:26.000
We just talked about the...

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:28.560
We only did the framework where we take the metrics

00:32:28.560 --> 00:32:31.719
and build something that relates players to teams.

00:32:31.719 --> 00:32:33.239
But we didn't do anything

00:32:33.239 --> 00:32:34.439
where we account for who they play.

00:32:34.439 --> 00:32:36.439
And we know that some of these players

00:32:36.439 --> 00:32:38.920
at the bigger conference schools play harder schedules

00:32:38.920 --> 00:32:40.959
than the ones at smaller conference schools.

00:32:40.959 --> 00:32:43.000
So, what do we do, right?

00:32:45.959 --> 00:32:47.400
So, we moved to part two, right?

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:50.760
This is where we get really in-depth

00:32:50.760 --> 00:32:53.920
about how to take a thing, which, again,

00:32:53.920 --> 00:32:55.760
was a bunch of math to get here,

00:32:55.760 --> 00:32:57.199
and now we take it to the next level

00:32:57.199 --> 00:32:58.959
with sort of statistical analysis.

00:32:58.959 --> 00:33:02.359
And again, we'll see how R and BigQuery can help with that.

00:33:02.359 --> 00:33:03.239
So, we talked about this.

00:33:03.239 --> 00:33:05.040
Teams face varying levels of competition.

00:33:05.079 --> 00:33:06.920
So, there's 350 plus Division I teams

00:33:06.920 --> 00:33:09.920
that are organized into 32 conferences.

00:33:09.920 --> 00:33:11.439
They play largely different opponents.

00:33:11.439 --> 00:33:14.119
Some conferences are traditionally better than others.

00:33:14.119 --> 00:33:16.839
Also, if you think about what affects performance,

00:33:16.839 --> 00:33:18.280
home court advantage matters, right?

00:33:18.280 --> 00:33:19.439
So, if you're playing at home a lot,

00:33:19.439 --> 00:33:22.959
you may likely do better than if you play on the road more.

00:33:23.880 --> 00:33:25.599
And this middle section here,

00:33:25.599 --> 00:33:28.199
we have a model representation kind of of what happens.

00:33:28.199 --> 00:33:33.199
So, a player or a team stat is maybe loosely related

00:33:34.199 --> 00:33:36.280
to the intercept, sort of like a baseline,

00:33:36.280 --> 00:33:38.680
plus maybe the team effect.

00:33:38.680 --> 00:33:40.119
Again, plus could be plus or minus,

00:33:40.119 --> 00:33:42.520
maybe the team's above average or below average.

00:33:43.479 --> 00:33:45.760
The effect of the opponent, right, who they're playing,

00:33:45.760 --> 00:33:48.439
as well as maybe some impact from home

00:33:48.439 --> 00:33:52.040
and being at home or on the road or a neutral site.

00:33:52.040 --> 00:33:53.479
And then, again, error, right?

00:33:53.479 --> 00:33:55.839
So, if we think of fitting a model like this,

00:33:55.839 --> 00:33:58.079
again, very high-level loose representation,

00:33:59.199 --> 00:34:01.800
we can kind of directly measure the effects of team

00:34:01.839 --> 00:34:05.880
versus opponent and, again, home court on every stat.

00:34:05.880 --> 00:34:09.679
So, we use FlimNet, which is a common package

00:34:09.679 --> 00:34:12.919
in sort of the regularized regression space

00:34:12.919 --> 00:34:14.360
to fit a bridge regression.

00:34:14.360 --> 00:34:16.159
Bridge regression helps with sort of,

00:34:16.159 --> 00:34:18.120
like I said, regularization,

00:34:18.120 --> 00:34:21.560
not like accounting for sort of outliers, small samples,

00:34:21.560 --> 00:34:26.320
as well as still giving us good estimates of these effects.

00:34:26.320 --> 00:34:27.360
And the interesting part here

00:34:27.360 --> 00:34:29.080
is we're not fitting a model for predictions.

00:34:29.080 --> 00:34:30.840
We're fitting a model to get coefficients

00:34:30.840 --> 00:34:33.719
that we can use to get estimates

00:34:33.719 --> 00:34:36.120
for offensive and defensive efficiency,

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:38.719
effective offensive and defensive efficiency on teams

00:34:38.719 --> 00:34:42.080
and home court advantage, as well.

00:34:42.080 --> 00:34:44.280
So, we're more interested in the coefficients of this model

00:34:44.280 --> 00:34:46.320
than any prediction, at least initially.

00:34:46.320 --> 00:34:48.520
And I think, like I said, once I share these slides,

00:34:48.520 --> 00:34:50.479
you'll see a little bit more details.

00:34:51.959 --> 00:34:54.280
So, that we use to adjust offensive

00:34:54.280 --> 00:34:56.040
and defensive efficiency for teams.

00:34:57.080 --> 00:35:00.600
But the last thing, we are interested in players.

00:35:01.360 --> 00:35:03.560
So, once we have an adjusted team rating,

00:35:03.560 --> 00:35:05.399
what do we do for the player side?

00:35:05.399 --> 00:35:08.760
Well, you can see, we wanna adjust at the rating level.

00:35:08.760 --> 00:35:11.959
So, we can adjust player's offensive and defensive ratings

00:35:11.959 --> 00:35:16.719
by the opponent's ratings on the other side of the ball.

00:35:16.719 --> 00:35:18.280
So, if I'm on offense,

00:35:18.280 --> 00:35:21.439
my rating should be adjusted for home court,

00:35:21.439 --> 00:35:24.000
as well as the opponent's defense.

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:26.879
And then my defense should be adjusted for their offense.

00:35:26.879 --> 00:35:28.600
So, those are the two sort of formulas you see here.

00:35:28.600 --> 00:35:30.120
They're pretty actually straightforward.

00:35:30.120 --> 00:35:31.199
Once you have these ratings,

00:35:31.199 --> 00:35:34.520
the adjustments are essentially linear combinations

00:35:34.520 --> 00:35:36.399
of this on the game level.

00:35:36.399 --> 00:35:39.040
So, a player's adjusted offensive rating in a game

00:35:39.040 --> 00:35:40.000
might go up or down.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:42.000
If he's at home, it'll go down,

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:43.360
usually about two points or so,

00:35:43.360 --> 00:35:45.159
points for 100 possessions.

00:35:45.159 --> 00:35:48.120
And then opponent adjustment can vary a lot.

00:35:48.120 --> 00:35:49.479
You may play a really hard opponent

00:35:49.479 --> 00:35:53.360
and your offense rating will jump about 20 points or so.

00:35:53.360 --> 00:35:56.399
Again, the level, it's on a points for 100 possession level.

00:35:56.399 --> 00:35:58.520
So, the average is about 100.

00:35:58.520 --> 00:36:00.320
But it also could go down 20 points or so.

00:36:00.320 --> 00:36:03.679
And defense rating, you see a little bit like that as well.

00:36:04.639 --> 00:36:07.159
And then, once you adjust these ratings,

00:36:07.159 --> 00:36:08.800
you can aggregate those to the season level

00:36:08.800 --> 00:36:11.120
and then follow that same diagram we had before,

00:36:11.120 --> 00:36:12.280
where you go boom, boom, boom,

00:36:12.280 --> 00:36:14.080
to get adjusted win shares,

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:16.840
adjusted wins above average, and those sorts of things.

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:23.320
