00:48:29.120 --> 00:48:30.600
where I did stuff in BigQuery a little more,

00:48:30.600 --> 00:48:31.840
then I did some in R a little more.

00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:32.959
There's always trade-offs.

00:48:32.959 --> 00:48:34.719
It depends on what you want to do with the data,

00:48:34.719 --> 00:48:37.320
where it may be at the time, what you're comfortable with,

00:48:37.320 --> 00:48:38.560
what your colleagues are comfortable with.

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:42.320
So, that's kind of a journey you go on as a data scientist.

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:43.760
And yeah, this is pretty hard.

00:48:43.760 --> 00:48:46.360
I think there's a lot here that we went through,

00:48:46.360 --> 00:48:49.479
but we got to rate all Division I men's

00:48:49.520 --> 00:48:53.360
and women's basketball players over nine years

00:48:53.360 --> 00:48:56.760
with open source data, R, and a version of BigQuery

00:48:56.760 --> 00:48:59.639
that you could probably use within the free tier

00:48:59.639 --> 00:49:00.520
in terms of number of storage.

00:49:00.520 --> 00:49:02.120
So, that's pretty cool, I think.

00:49:03.879 --> 00:49:06.399
Okay, and finally, my sports analytics takeaways.

00:49:07.560 --> 00:49:10.399
So, there's large open source data resources.

00:49:10.399 --> 00:49:11.919
I talked about the Sports Dataverse.

00:49:11.919 --> 00:49:14.040
Shout out to Sime again.

00:49:14.040 --> 00:49:15.360
Allows you to do this stuff.

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:17.719
Allows anyone to kind of get started if you have R

00:49:17.719 --> 00:49:19.760
without doing a ton of setup.

00:49:20.800 --> 00:49:23.439
We noticed how having sports knowledge

00:49:23.439 --> 00:49:25.439
and using established work in this field

00:49:25.439 --> 00:49:26.560
isn't really important, right?

00:49:26.560 --> 00:49:28.320
So, I didn't have to build a framework from scratch

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:30.959
about how to turn box score stats into wins.

00:49:30.959 --> 00:49:32.879
There are better and more advanced ones

00:49:32.879 --> 00:49:34.560
than the ones I use, but the ones I use

00:49:34.560 --> 00:49:37.239
are pretty well respected and established,

00:49:37.239 --> 00:49:39.199
and we can implement them.

00:49:39.199 --> 00:49:43.159
So, again, I heard a quote that said,

00:49:43.159 --> 00:49:46.080
like, good developers copy, great developers paste.

00:49:46.080 --> 00:49:48.000
So, I think the same things apply

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:49.679
to data scientists sometimes.

00:49:49.679 --> 00:49:50.959
Of course, we had to modify a bunch,

00:49:50.959 --> 00:49:53.159
but it gives us a huge head start.

00:49:53.159 --> 00:49:56.679
Schedule adjustment is important, especially in college,

00:49:56.679 --> 00:49:58.919
and Alia Boston and Oscar Shiboi

00:49:58.919 --> 00:50:00.239
are really good at basketball.

