00:57:37.560 --> 00:57:40.719
So I was just wondering if you have any specific experiences

00:57:40.719 --> 00:57:44.280
using, well, first using,

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:47.479
I guess you would call it soccer data

00:57:47.479 --> 00:57:50.040
and also doing the analysis.

00:57:50.040 --> 00:57:51.320
And what have been your,

00:57:53.199 --> 00:57:54.239
if you've done it,

00:57:54.239 --> 00:57:57.199
what have been the specific challenges, if you will?

00:57:58.760 --> 00:58:01.719
Yeah, so I've used soccer data on and off

00:58:01.719 --> 00:58:04.000
for almost 10 years now also.

00:58:04.959 --> 00:58:08.840
So I think one of the major challenges in soccer

00:58:08.840 --> 00:58:10.360
is that it's low scoring.

00:58:10.360 --> 00:58:11.360
So unlike basketball here,

00:58:11.360 --> 00:58:13.199
where we can almost do everything off of points

00:58:13.199 --> 00:58:15.000
per possession or whatever,

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:18.560
soccer, lots of matches end one nil,

00:58:20.040 --> 00:58:22.520
no nil draws, pretty common, right?

00:58:22.520 --> 00:58:24.479
Did anyone do anything in this match?

00:58:24.479 --> 00:58:25.320
So of course they did.

00:58:25.320 --> 00:58:26.399
They ran around for 90 minutes,

00:58:26.399 --> 00:58:27.600
they fastballed, tried to do a bunch of stuff.

00:58:27.600 --> 00:58:32.360
So there's been a lot of work over a while now

00:58:32.360 --> 00:58:35.600
on sort of like how to measure team and player performance

00:58:35.600 --> 00:58:37.879
based on the actions that are taken,

00:58:37.879 --> 00:58:39.280
not just scoring goals.

00:58:40.320 --> 00:58:41.679
This expected goals framework

00:58:41.719 --> 00:58:42.919
has gotten really popular

00:58:42.919 --> 00:58:45.560
amongst every sort of place in soccer,

00:58:45.560 --> 00:58:47.679
or you may call it football that I know of.

00:58:47.679 --> 00:58:50.840
So that is different ways of calculating

00:58:50.840 --> 00:58:52.560
based on where every shot came from,

00:58:52.560 --> 00:58:54.040
because you'll have way more shots generally

00:58:54.040 --> 00:58:55.199
than you'll have goals.

00:58:56.040 --> 00:58:57.439
Assigning a value for,

00:58:59.120 --> 00:59:00.479
assigning a value for the probability

00:59:00.479 --> 00:59:01.520
that the shot would go in,

00:59:01.520 --> 00:59:03.159
and then sort of aggregating that value.

00:59:03.159 --> 00:59:05.760
So there's often soccer matches

00:59:05.760 --> 00:59:06.639
because scoring is so low

00:59:06.639 --> 00:59:09.080
where the best team doesn't kind of win, right?

00:59:09.080 --> 00:59:10.639
If you watch one team have more chances,

00:59:10.639 --> 00:59:11.679
one team had more opportunities,

00:59:11.679 --> 00:59:12.520
but they just missed them,

00:59:12.520 --> 00:59:14.520
or the keeper was really amazing.

00:59:15.360 --> 00:59:16.959
Expected goals helps tell that story.

00:59:16.959 --> 00:59:19.120
And it turns out it's also very predictive as well

00:59:19.120 --> 00:59:21.879
from team performance better than goals itself

00:59:21.879 --> 00:59:23.199
in a lot of cases.

00:59:23.199 --> 00:59:24.760
So that's one thing to kind of,

00:59:25.679 --> 00:59:27.080
to know and to keep in mind.

00:59:27.080 --> 00:59:29.879
Nowadays, like in every other sport, there's tracking data.

00:59:29.879 --> 00:59:31.439
So you can get a lot more information

00:59:31.439 --> 00:59:32.840
about what's going on in the soccer matches

00:59:32.840 --> 00:59:34.159
than it was, you know,

00:59:35.280 --> 00:59:36.120
to one.

00:59:37.080 --> 00:59:37.919
Yeah.

00:59:37.919 --> 00:59:40.520
And that series I have linked in there on BigQuery

00:59:41.360 --> 00:59:43.000
does take you through taking soccer event data

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:44.639
and building an expected goals model.

00:59:44.639 --> 00:59:47.600
So if that's of interest, I would recommend taking a look.

00:59:50.520 --> 00:59:51.360
Thanks.

00:59:52.560 --> 00:59:53.399
Thank you.

00:59:55.040 --> 00:59:57.439
One anonymous question on Slido was,

00:59:57.439 --> 00:59:59.800
how do you decide what to adjust on?

00:59:59.800 --> 01:00:02.159
For example, like home court advantage,

01:00:02.159 --> 01:00:04.239
what are some of the less obvious ones?

01:00:05.560 --> 01:00:07.159
Yeah, good question.

01:00:07.159 --> 01:00:09.760
You can adjust for a lot.

01:00:09.760 --> 01:00:13.360
So when we, at ESPN, we're building models

01:00:13.360 --> 01:00:16.959
to predict college football and college basketball games.

01:00:16.959 --> 01:00:18.679
The main thing to adjust for is like,

01:00:18.679 --> 01:00:19.840
again, this is going backwards,

01:00:19.840 --> 01:00:22.360
but then also forwards is who you're playing, right?

01:00:22.360 --> 01:00:24.239
So the opponent's gonna dictate the most.

01:00:24.239 --> 01:00:26.679
Home court advantage is usually the second most,

01:00:26.679 --> 01:00:29.040
second biggest factor if you're talking about things

01:00:29.040 --> 01:00:31.800
that are sort of quantifiable on the game level.

01:00:31.800 --> 01:00:34.800
But then there's other things, days rest, distance traveled.

01:00:34.800 --> 01:00:37.360
Those are things that we started incorporating in the model.

01:00:37.360 --> 01:00:39.520
The average, if you're thinking about this in terms of gain,

01:00:40.280 --> 01:00:41.120
you're gonna get your biggest gain from the opponent,

01:00:41.120 --> 01:00:42.639
then a little more maybe from home court,

01:00:42.639 --> 01:00:44.959
and then it's sort of marginal.

01:00:44.959 --> 01:00:47.959
But days rest is important in some sports,

01:00:47.959 --> 01:00:49.520
especially if there's a discrepancy, right?

01:00:49.520 --> 01:00:52.919
So we, you know, sometimes a team has a week off,

01:00:52.919 --> 01:00:55.080
another team just played recently,

01:00:55.080 --> 01:00:56.760
so there's an advantage there.

01:00:56.760 --> 01:00:59.600
Distance traveled, I think some of my colleagues

01:00:59.600 --> 01:01:01.520
at ESPN have found altitude effects, right?

01:01:01.520 --> 01:01:04.560
So if you look at which teams have

01:01:04.560 --> 01:01:05.760
the highest home court advantage

01:01:05.760 --> 01:01:07.879
in college and pro basketball,

01:01:07.879 --> 01:01:11.800
it's the teams that play in Utah and Denver almost always.

01:01:11.800 --> 01:01:16.120
And it's because I think we at least suspect the altitude,

01:01:16.120 --> 01:01:17.959
the teams that are there are used to playing there,

01:01:17.959 --> 01:01:21.399
and the road teams have trouble catching their breath.

01:01:21.399 --> 01:01:23.239
So those sorts of things are interesting.

01:01:23.239 --> 01:01:25.679
You can, if you get really into the player modeling aspect,

01:01:25.679 --> 01:01:29.520
then you open up a whole can of adjustments.

01:01:29.520 --> 01:01:31.479
You adjust for who's on the court,

01:01:31.479 --> 01:01:33.800
who's on the pitch, whatever,

01:01:33.800 --> 01:01:36.560
in sort of these other frameworks like adjusted plus minus,

01:01:36.600 --> 01:01:39.080
which have become popular over the years as well.

